You are at the animal pens.
You're reaching the end of the animal exhibits. To the north, you see a caravan trailer. A trash heap is visible to the northwest through the slats of the fence.  You can see - and smell - an outhouse to the west.  The carnival's backstage alley begins to the east, behind a tarp with a sign above it.
You can go south, east, northwest, north or west.

You startle when suddenly a tall thin clown emerges from the alley to the east, brushing you aside.  This clown is absurdly tall and thin; he towers above you, moving as gracefully as a deer on his long, stilt-like legs, his white conical hat nearly brushing the electric lighting wires haphazardly strung up over the alleyway.  His baggy white suit is spotless and immaculately pressed, but he's so thin that this only makes him look more like a scarecrow.  His face is painted completely white, except for the black stars around his eyes -- which are so small and set into his face that they look like pinpricks of light in an endless white plane.  He looks right at you, but acts as though he doesn't see you.

He extends to his full height, like a spider unfolding from its hole, and strides off down the alleyway between the animal pens.  As he passes, you notice his feet are thorny and calloused, split into three taloned toes each, like the feet of a chicken. Then you blink and he's gone.

Well.  You probably just imagined that thing about his feet, really.
