> give corncob to clown

> give corncob to clown
The clown's little piggy eyes light up as you hold up the battered corncob. The clown drops the corndog nub and grabs the new "corndog" out of your hands so fast that he nearly rips your fingers off.

He shoves it into his mouth and clamps down. The ear-splitting crack of teeth against cob shatters the air.  The clown drops the corncob and falls to the ground, whining in pain.

You've got a clear shot, so... why not? You kick the clown right in his fat forehead, resulting in yet another loud ear-splitting crack, and the fat clown is out cold.
> n

> n

You are in the Big Top.
You can see a multitude of clowns.
You can go south or down.
The Big Top is filled with chortling and chuckling and whooping. It takes a few moments for your eyes to adjust to the gloom, but when they do you see that the Big Top is filled with clowns: Big ones, little ones, all shapes and sizes, all the colors of the rainbow.  There's an almost overpowering smell of burnt rubber.

Luckily, in your ventriloquist dummy disguise, they don't seem to notice you.

The clowns fill the bleachers where the audience would usually sit, grunting and shouting..  And right there, in the center of the ring, you see a familiar face: It's T.I. Urge the ringmaster! The guy who gave you your free ticket! A small hunched clown painted coal black crouches next to him.

At his feet, you see two other familiar faces. Red and Mugsy. They're wrapped up in sticky cocoons like two flies caught in a spider's web and they're lying very still.

There's also a pit dug in the center of the ring.

"The Clownqueror Worm was born in fire and ash and pain, the dying screams of the innocent and the agonized gasps of the pure. Its rage is blinding, its hunger eternal!"

A murmur ripples through the crowd around you; you catch a few slurred words and you realize that they're repeating his words back. It seems to be some sort of call-and-response prayer ritual, except half of the crowd doesn't seem to be capable of speech. You watch as misshapen mouths ill-suited to forming words drool and blubber with the effort of fitting together syllables.

"It rises eternal, long in coil, deep in maw, hungry always for new flesh. It made up, the clownkin for one purpose, to bring sustenance... and sustenance we bring! For the Clownqueror Worm!"
The clown crowd whoops and hollers, but T.I. Urge raises his hand for silence.

"Wait," says T.I. Urge, "Where's the third one? There were supposed to be at least THREE urchins. Where's the third one!?"

"She keepsh moving," mutters the black-face clown, dribbling saliva.

"Well, never mind, we'll get her yet," says T.I Urge. He kicks the cocoons at his feet and both Red and Mugsy tumble into the pit, disappearing from sight without a sound.
The clowns start whooping again.

"Complete the ritual," shouts T.I. Urge, "I'm going to go find that last urchin. And remember, when we open to the public, any urchins that come then will be OURS."

He swaggers out through the back of the tent. The hollering dies down and the clowns return to a steady, rhythmic mumbling.
> x clowns

> x clowns
A whole lot of clowns: the way they're crouching, eager to spring, you would definitely call this a pack of clowns.

They're all quietly mumbling, staring intently ahead of them at nothing. They almost seem to be in some sort of religious trance.
> d

> d
While the clowns are distracted with their chanting, you scrabble for that pit in the center of the ring and duck down.  For a brief moment, you tumble through darkness... until you collide, hard, with a floor.

You are in an office.
You're in an office of some sort, covered in loose papers and assorted debris.

The room is dimly lit by some bioluminescent mold on the walls.
You can see a portrait, cocooned Red and cocooned Mugsy.
